aa(lp119
VAnd I know how we got here.
p120
aV(Applause)
p121
aa(lp122
VI know how we got here.
p123
aVYou know, there was institutionalized,
p124
aVat one time legalized, discrimination in our country.
p125
aVThere's no question about it.
p126
aVBut still, as I grapple with this issue,
p127
aVmy mother's question hangs in the air for me:
p128
aVHow did they treat you?
p129
aa(lp130
VNow, I do not raise this issue to complain
p131
aVor in any way to elicit any kind of sympathy.
p132
aVI have succeeded in my life
p133
aVbeyond my wildest expectations,
p134
aVand I have been treated well by people of all races
p135
aVmore often than I have not.
p136
aVI tell the uniform story because it happened.
p137
aVI cite those statistics around corporate board diversity
p138
aVbecause they are real,
p139
aVand I stand here today
p140
aVtalking about this issue of racial discrimination
p141
aVbecause I believe it threatens to rob
p142
aVanother generation of all the opportunities
p143
aVthat all of us want for all of our children,
p144
aVno matter what their color
p145
aVor where they come from.
p146
aVAnd I think it also threatens to hold back businesses.
p147
aVYou see, researchers have coined this term
p148
aV"color blindness"
p149
aVto describe a learned behavior where we pretend
p150
aVthat we don't notice race.
p151
aVIf you happen to be surrounded by a bunch of people
p152
aVwho look like you, that's purely accidental.
p153
aVNow, color blindness, in my view,
p154
aVdoesn't mean that there's no racial discrimination,
p155
aVand there's fairness.
p156
aVIt doesn't mean that at all. It doesn't ensure it.
p157
aVIn my view, color blindness is very dangerous
p158
aVbecause it means we're ignoring the problem.
p159
aVThere was a corporate study that said that,
p160
aVinstead of avoiding race,
p161
aVthe really smart corporations actually deal with it head on.
p162
aVThey actually recognize that embracing diversity
p163
aVmeans recognizing all races,
p164
aVincluding the majority one.
p165
aVBut I'll be the first one to tell you,
p166
aVthis subject matter can be hard,
p167
aVawkward, uncomfortable \u2014 but that's kind of the point.
p168
aa(lp169
VIn the spirit of debunking racial stereotypes,
p170
aVthe one that black people don't like to swim,
p171
aVI'm going to tell you how much I love to swim.
p172
aVI love to swim so much
p173
aVthat as an adult, I swim with a coach.
p174
aVAnd one day my coach had me do a drill
p175
aVwhere I had to swim to one end of a 25-meter pool
